04566nam a2200541Ia 9781438468310DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384683107 a10.1515/97814384683102doi  a(DE-B1597)681957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a185qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBos, Abraham P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAristotle on God's Life-Generating Power and on Pneuma as Its Vehicle /cAbraham P. Bos. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (340 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Ancient Greek Philosophy00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tGod’s Life-Generating Power and Its Transmission in Aristotle’s Biology and Cosmology -- tThe Dependence of All Nature upon God -- tThe Natural Desire of All Things for God -- tGod as Object of Erôs and Source of Attraction -- tGod as Unmoved Principle of Motion and Source of Power -- tReproduction -- tLife Begins at the Moment of Fertilization -- tThe Magnet as Model of a Mover at a Distance -- tGod as Begetter of All Life According to On the Cosmos -- tPneuma as the Vehicle of Divine Power in the Sublunary Region -- tDesire as a Form of Nostalgia for the Origin -- tWhy Doesn’t Pneuma Play an Important Role in Ancient and Modern Interpretations of Aristotle? -- tThe Dubious Lines of On the Soul II 1, 412b1–4 -- tWhy Can’t the Words Sôma Organikon in Aristotle’s Definition of the Soul Refer to the Visible Body? -- tCollateral Damage of the Hylomorphistic Explanation of Aristotle’s Psychology -- tResulting Damage to the Assessment of On the Cosmos and On the Life-Bearing Spirit (De Spiritu) -- tDamage to the View of the Unity of Aristotle’s Work -- tIntellect, Soul, and Entelechy -- tAristotle on Life-Bearing Pneuma and on God as Begetter of the Cosmos -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Modern Names -- tIndex of Ancient Names -- tIndex of Texts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this deep rethinking of Aristotle's work, Abraham P. Bos argues that scholarship on Aristotle's philosophy has erred since antiquity in denying the connection between his theology and his doctrine of reproduction and life in the earthly sphere. Beginning with an analysis of God's role in the Aristotelian system, Bos explores how this relates to other elements of his philosophy, especially to his theory of reproduction. The argument he develops is that in talking about the cosmos, Aristotle rejected Plato's metaphor of artisanal production by a divine Demiurge in favor of a biotic metaphor based on the transmission of life in reproduction, in which pneuma—not breath as it is often interpreted but the life-bearing spirit in animals and plants—plays a key and sustaining role as the vital principle in all that lives. In making this case, he defends the authenticity of the treatises De Mundo and De Spiritu as Aristotle's, and demonstrates Aristotle's works as a unified system that sharply and comprehensively refutes Plato's, and in particular replaces Plato's doctrine of the soul with a theory in which the soul is clearly distinguished from the intellect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGod. 0aReligion. 0aSoul. 0aSpirit. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846831040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438468310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438468310/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  